Photography & Imagery Style Guide
Art direction concept: The Working Watch — microbrands make watches to be worn, not preserved. Photography should convey life, craft, and environment.

Primary Photography Style
Macro precision shots: Close-up dial photography at f/2.8–f/4, shallow depth of field isolating texture detail. Lighting: single directional source (north window light or gridded softbox) to reveal case finishing and dial surface. No hero shots on pure white.
Environmental wear shots: Watch on wrist in considered but not staged settings — architect's desk, worn leather jacket cuff, boat rope, map on a table. Natural light. No jewelry, no Rolexes in the background, no aspirational lifestyle clichés.
Flat lay precision: Watch laid on raw materials relevant to the watch story — graphite slab, linen, Japanese washi paper, brushed steel. Neutral background always, never gradient fills or busy patterns.
Rejected aesthetics: No floating-in-white-void commercial shots, no glamour-lit Geneva-style product photography, no lifestyle shots with models in suits.
Color Treatment
Slight desaturation (-10 to -20%) to unify diverse brand photography
Slight cool shift on blues and greens to reinforce the precision-instrument aesthetic
Shadows: lift slightly (never crushed to black) — detail in shadow areas is essential for finishing evaluation
Do not apply Instagram-style presets. Consistency through restraint, not filter application.
Aspect Ratios
Hero banners:          16:9 (desktop) / 4:5 (mobile)
Brand cards:           3:2
Review feature:        16:9 (landscape) / square (social)
Dial detail shots:     1:1 only

Iconography, Patterns & Graphic Elements
Iconography system:

Line icons only — 1.5px stroke weight, rounded terminals, 24×24px grid
Category icons should be custom-drawn (not emoji or Font Awesome) — each should reference the watch category's heritage (e.g., dive: pressure gauge, pilot: compass rose as the P, field: topographic contour)
Never use filled icon variants alongside stroke icons in the same context
Graphic patterns:

Chapter Ring Grid: A subtle background pattern derived from a watch bezel chapter ring — evenly spaced minute markers in 1px lines at 6° intervals. Use at 5–8% opacity on dark backgrounds for section separators and card backgrounds. Never at full opacity.
Dial Texture: Crosshatch/guilloché-inspired micro-texture (think sunburst or satin brushed grain) rendered as a CSS/SVG pattern for hero backgrounds. 3% opacity maximum.
Hairline Rules: 0.5px horizontal rules in Caseback Silver (#9BA0A8) for section separation — replacing full-bleed dividers. Adds precision-instrument feel.
Arc Element: A partial circle arc (the "crown" shape) — 120° arc segment used as a graphic accent in hero sections, pulled from the watch crown profile.
Mood Board Description
Reference direction 1 — Nordic Precision:
Spread of a Baltic watch on rough linen, single north-facing window light, deep shadows in the case flanks, entire image desaturated to near-monochrome except the warm gilt printing on the dial. Feels like a specialist magazine from Stockholm.

Reference direction 2 — Tool Watch Heritage:
A Halios Seaforth photographed against a scuffed aluminum workshop surface. One LED lamp casting a hard shadow. The watch is clearly a working object. Copy overlaid in Syne 700, Lume Green.

Reference direction 3 — Dial Abstraction:
Extreme macro of an AnOrdain enamel dial — the texture reads as almost geological. Used as a full-bleed hero background with the headline reversed out in Archive White. Category: Dress/Art.

Reference direction 4 — Map & Provenance:
A Formex Element shot on a faded topographic map of the Swiss Jura mountains. Establishes geographic origin as part of brand storytelling — used in the "brands by country" section.

Reference direction 5 — The Collector's Desk:
Wide shot: notebook with watch sketches, a Serica 5303 face-up on the leather surface, JetBrains Mono price spec set in the corner. Editorial and intelligent. Community-coded.

Reference direction 6 — Dark Mode Luxury:
Black background. A single applied index illuminated by a lume macro shot — electric green glow. Almost no other detail visible. The tagline "Every Independent Watch. One Trusted Source." appears below in Archive White. Minimal, authoritative, slightly cinematic.

